column1: # This row, and all below it, are comments because they all begin with a hashtag character (#) in column A.
# This is Mark's Google Sheet titled 'DGImportTemplate'.  It is provided as a good example of how to layout data for CSV import into Digital Grinnell.
# The data here is representative of the 'Ancient Coins' collection held in Digital Grinnell.   The above data has been imported into 5 objects that may be found
# Note that the CSV import process has the ability to read a special 'constants' CSV file so that values which are IDENTICAL in every object record can be entered once
# for import...these values do not have to be entered for every object!  A sample constants file is included in the DGConstantsTemplate tab of this sheet.
# Conventions for content of an import spreadsheet (actually a CSV or TSV file) can be found in https://github.com/DigitalGrinnell/icg_csv_import/blob/development/README.md.
# If you are appending data into an existing collection, experience suggests that the best way to determine the xpaths (row 1) for your fields is to examine, as an administrator,
# the MODS datastreams of three or more representative objects in that collection (for example, go to http://dgadmin.grinnell.edu/islandora/object/test:22198/datastream/MODS/view).
# It is important to sample from more than one object (hence we recommend three or more representative objects) since not all objects contain ALL possible MODS fields.
# When you are ready to import data it is suggested that you save your spreadsheet as a TSV (tab-separated values) file.  To do so from Google Sheets simply use
# the following menu selections...   File | Download as... | Tab-separated values (.tsv, current sheet).  This will export a TSV copy of the data to your computer and
# the instructions in https://github.com/DigitalGrinnell/icg_csv_import/blob/development/README.md can then be used to process that file (or you may want to enlist the help
# of your friendly, neighborhood system admin).
